To make the case plainer, by contrasting it with one somewhat similar, suppose it is said: No proposition is true. If granted, the pro- position itself is not true; and being false, some propositions must be true. Yes, but if denied, no difficulty follows. This is simply an absurdity akin to the Sceptical position: It is incluln‘table that every proposition is doubtful. It is only on one side that such utterances resemble insolubles: the essence of the latter consists in their being equally impossible to deny or to affirm,

Does a man who swears that he is committing perjury forswear himself or not? Not unless he speaks the truth3 and if he is speaking the truth, how can what he says be perjury? Can any one believe that he is mistaken in that very belief of his mistake?

The puzzle seems still more intricate when a decision has, one way or the other, to be taken in consequence. A certain Greek rheto- rician taught his art to a young man, Half his fee was paid down in advance; the other half was to be paid when, and only when, he gained his first suit. Or the following: A tyrant sets men at a bridge which is his pro- perty, with the order to ask every passenger whether he will pass or no, and allow only those to pass who answer truly. If he says: “I shall pass over,³’ he can either be allowed to pass, or be turned back, and proved thus to have told an untruth; but what of the man who says: “I shall not pass?³' If they turn him back, he has spoken the truth, and they fail in their duty; if they make him pass, they fail equally, for he has uttered a falsehood.
